content.text:
I've been working on this "minimal CSS to make websites not suck" challenge for a while and I think I've whittled it down into something more reasonable and less opinionated. The biggest struggle has been the relationship between the sizes of  `<h1>` through `<h6>`, which seems like it should follow a predictable function.

![Screenshot from 2019-06-02 10-10-07.png](&aJyga5iQajGa+4EXCI5U3ApeCYvwGrLBOG7kxySRCQs=.sha256)

My goal is to add some sane typographic defaults without overriding any custom preferences (e.g. base font size). Here's the CSS I'm using:

```css
html {
  /* default to OS font or choose something non-crappy */
  font-family: system-ui, 
  -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 
  "Segoe UI", "Roboto", "Oxygen", 
  "Ubuntu", "Cantarell", "Fira Sans", 
  "Droid Sans", "Helvetica Neue", sans-serif;

  /* basic typography */
  line-height: 1.33;
}

/* https://www.desmos.com/calculator/3elcf5cwhn */
h1 { font-size: 150%; }
h2 { font-size: 128%; }
h3 { font-size: 120%; }
h4 { font-size: 116%; }
h5 { font-size: 113%; }
h6 { font-size: 111%; }

@media screen {
  html {
    /* expand to full screen for easy centering */
    min-height: 100%;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;

    /* center <body> on the screen */
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
  }
  body {
    /* reasonable line width and padding (for <html> backgrounds)*/
    max-width: 36rem;
    padding: 1rem;
  }
}
```
